<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900507-0022</DOCNO><DOCID>900507-0022.</DOCID><HL>   New Hampshire   Savings Bank Posts   Loss for First Quarter</HL><DATE>05/07/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9E</SO><CO>   NHSB</CO><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)</IN><LP>   CONCORD, N.H. -- New Hampshire Savings Bank Corp. reporteda first-quarter net loss of $6.7 million, or $1.09 a share,and warned that its turnaround strategy has &quot;experiencedsetbacks in the face of a weakening economy.&quot;   In the year-ago quarter, the thrift reported a net loss of$6 million, or 97 cents a share. Like other New Englandfinancial institutions, New Hampshire Savings's performancehas been battered by a sluggish economy and floundering realestate market.</LP><TEXT>   In the latest quarter, New Hampshire Savings took aprovision for credit losses of $6.4 million, compared to a$9.4 million provision in the year-earlier quarter. Itcurrently has a $58.1 million allowance for credit losses,nearly four times the yearago level.   The bank said that its nonperforming assets now amount to9.6% of its $1.38 billion in assets. That's three times theyearago level of nonperformers and slightly wider than thelevel three months ago. Its allowance for credit losses is43.5% of its actual nonperforming assets.   Joseph J. Butare Jr., chairman, said that &quot;our ability toimplement our (turnaround) plan successfully depends on avariety of factors, many of them beyond our control.&quot;   He said that the bank's primary capital ratio declinedslightly to 5.74% from the year-end level, and remained belowthe 6% regulatory minimum capital requirement.   He said the bank had asked the Federal Deposit InsuranceCorporation to extend a temporary waiver allowing it tocontinue to accept &quot;brokered deposits on which its liquidityin large part depends.&quot;   The bank also said that it has received from the FDIC adraft consent cease and desist order covering almost allaspects of its operations. Such orders have been signed byseveral troubled area banks.   Mr. Butare said that he is working to reduce the size ofthe bank and its costs. He said total assets have beenreduced 10% in the past year; the bank has cut its work force10% as well.   He added, &quot;We don't expect the economy to rebound in thenear term, and (we) continue to strengthen measures tosafeguard asset quality against what promise to remaindifficult and challenging conditions.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>